    a3: 'Wychwood has a distinctive mix of older heritage homes around Wychwood Barns and Hillcrest Village, with a roughly even split between gas and electric stoves. Older Kenmore and GE models are the dominant brands in both categories. For gas stoves, igniter electrode wear is the top call: years of use erode the electrode tip and the burner starts clicking repeatedly without lighting. Bake igniter failure is closely behind — the oven does not heat because the aging igniter cannot open the gas safety valve. For electric stoves, which are common in renovated Wychwood kitchens, heating element failure is the top call: a surface element or bake element stops working, often showing a visible burn or crack on the element coil. Temperature sensor failure — the thermistor inside the oven cavity — is a distinctive Wychwood electric range issue: the oven runs significantly too hot or too cold, and the thermistor resistance is out of specification. Older Kenmore electric models from the 2000s are particularly prone to thermistor failure over time.',
